## W3C’s Requirements for CGs

As per [W3C community process guidelines](https://www.w3.org/community/about/), Community Groups (CGs) are established for communities of stakeholders to socialize their ideas for possible future standardization. The W3C requirements for CGs include:

*   CGs must be public, open to all, without fee
*   CGs are Intellectual Property Rights (IPR) Balanced
*   CGs allowed to be self determined and exist without a time limit.
*   CGs are tuned for creating reports that are a transition to standards track, but there is no requirement that CG Reports advance to the standards track.
*   CGs may choose to develop test suites, white papers, demos, or merely to hold discussions.
*   CG Drafts and Final Reports must not suggest that they are standards or on the W3C standards-track.

In the context of the larger W3C process, Community Groups can publish documents with relatively minimal [process](https://www.w3.org/community/about/faq/#how-do-we-publish-a-specification), content [requirements](https://www.w3.org/community/reports/reqs/) other than a [contributor license agreement](https://www.w3.org/community/about/agreements/cla/). Community documents are listed as either [Community Final Reports](https://www.w3.org/community/reports/) (with a final date and list of licensing commitments) or as Community Drafts (without a date or list of licensing commitments). For example, see the reports listed on the Web Payments CG’s W3C [home](https://www.w3.org/community/webpayments/) page.


## Credentials Community Group Mission

To recap the specific mission of W3C Credentials Community Group (revised and accepted in [October 2017](https://www.w3.org/community/credentials/charter/)):


    The mission of the W3C Credentials Community Group is to explore the creation, storage, presentation, verification, and user control of credentials. We focus on a verifiable credential (a set of claims) created by an issuer about a subject—a person, group, or thing—and seek solutions inclusive of approaches such as: self-sovereign identity; presentation of proofs by the bearer; data minimization; and centralized, federated, and decentralized registry and identity systems. Our tasks include drafting and incubating Internet specifications for further standardization and prototyping and testing reference implementations.


### Scope of Work

In general, any work that advances the mission is welcome for consideration as a Work Item. A Work Item requires at least one group member willing to commit to being the first editor, another group member (from a different company) willing to be a co-editor, a suggested timeline, and the expected Work Item type, e.g., Community Final Report or Ongoing Repository.

All CCG Work Items are expected to eventually be published as “official” output of the CCG on the [W3C website for the CCG](https://www.w3.org/community/credentials/). Any other tasks of the CCG will be managed informally and will not use this Work Item process. 


### Types of Work Items

All Work Items fall into the following types:

*   **Community Reports** — a collaborative document, with the goal of being completed and published by the CCG as a [Final Report](https://www.w3.org/community/reports/reqs/) on [W3C website for the CCG](https://www.w3.org/community/credentials/). Community Reports must not suggest that they are standards or on the W3C standards-track.
    *   There are three kinds of Community Reports, each of which has the goal of transitioning to a Community Final Report as follows:
        *   **Community Specification**— A Final Report, with intended transition to becoming an official standards-track Working Group [Candidate Recommendation](https://www.w3.org/2005/10/Process-20051014/tr.html#q74). Example: [Decentralized Identifiers (DIDs)](https://w3c-ccg.github.io/did-spec/)
        *   **Community Note** — A Final Report, with intended transition to becoming an official W3C Working Group [Note](https://www.w3.org/2005/10/Process-20051014/tr.html#q75).
        *   **Community Commentary**— A Final Report not intended to transition to any official W3C Working Groups.
        *   (Do we need a category for non-W3C technical work. External or non-w3c specification)
    *   In our CCG process, Community Reports have 5 stages: 
        *   **Rough Draft** (not published in the CCG repo, for instance in a Google Doc)
        *   **Unreleased Draft** (iterated using a CCG repo but not tagged with a numbered release)
        *   **Released Draft** (tagged with numbered release but not published to W3C)
        *   **Published Draft**  (a tagged released vetted by CCG chairs for listing and announcement to W3C members as a Published Draft)
        *   **Final Report** (formally finalized & approved by CCG, submitted to the W3C to be listed as a Final Report, with announcement to W3C members as a Final Report from the CCG).
*   **Ongoing Community Drafts **— A Work Item with a repository that will be maintained by the CCG in perpetuity, May be listed by the CCG in as a “Community Draft” on [W3C Credentials Community Page](https://www.w3.org/community/credentials/), but never intended to be listed as a “Community Final Report”. Examples include registries, conformance tests, schemas, reference code, etc. _(Long term these may be replaced by new W3C processes, but currently as Working Groups currently terminate, until a new process for these is created by the W3C we maintain them as community groups are perpetual.)_
    *   **Conformance Test Suite** — a special form of repository, with the goal as being a companion to a specification community report for testing of conformance.
    *   **Registry** — a special form of repository, with the goal of providing an informative, long-lived list (such as credential status methods, DID methods, Linked Data Key Types)
    *   **Schema**
    *   **Reference Code**


### IP Release



*   All substantive contributors to any CCG Work Items must be members of the CCG with full IPR agreements signed. [https://www.w3.org/community/credentials/join](https://www.w3.org/community/credentials/join)
    *   Ensure you have a W3 account: https://www.w3.org/accounts/request
