A Work Item Proposal must include



1. Abstract or Draft of proposed Work Item (typically a link to a google doc or a markdown page in Github)
2. Editors responsible for advancing the Work Item. (Proposals may have a single editor; however, before approval of a Work Item it must have more than one editor, and editors must include representation from at least two companies.)

Note: the Github Work Item template auto-populates the following fields:



*   Labels the issue as “Proposed Work Item”
*   Prompts to add the editors’ contact information and Github handles to the issue

_NOTE: Do not create a new ccg repo in the CCG Community Github  (if you need a repo, create one in your personal Github account, and we can move it if the proposal is approved.)_

Once the Work Item Proposal issue exists, post an announcement about the proposal to the CCG mailing list Credentials Community Group &lt;[public-credentials@w3.org](mailto:public-credentials@w3.org)> with a link to the Github issue.


#### Adoption

Once proposed, the community group will discuss it for a period of at least one week. This discussion may take place on the mailing list as well as on the regular conference call at the Chairs discretion. During this time, proposers should seek support and consensus around the specific proposal. 

Once there has been suitable opportunity for conversation, the chairs have made a determination about appropriateness, there is sufficient community support, and there are no principled objections, the chairs will formally accept the Work Item.


#### Community Report Drafts

Once approved and if appropriate, the Chairs will create a dedicated repo within the CCG Github account. The editors will facilitate CCG members contributions to iterate on the document as per W3C github cultural practices including transparency and public documentation of work item meetings. To manage the intellectual property of contributions, editors should maintain the Work Item Drafts repo with the most up-to-date version of the work. 


#### Closure

Work Items that succeed in becoming Community Final Reports are closed. The existing CCG repo description will be noted as being “FINAL:”

If the chairs determine that progress on a Work Item is not progressing satisfactorily, they will notify the editors that they have one month to demonstrate progress. After this notice it is at the chairs discretion to keep the Work Item in the CCG roadmap, change the editors for the Work Item, or remove the Work Item from the CCG roadmap and formally close the work item, and the existing CCG repo description will be noted as being “CLOSED:”


### Community Report Stages


#### Rough Draft

**Rough Draft **— A version of a COMMUNITY REPORT Work Item not in a CCG repo that was created and iterated in whatever medium or format the editors favor, e.g., Google Docs, Github, etc.



*   An initial Rough Draft should be started by the Work Item proposed editors as part of the process of proposing a COMMUNITY REPORT Work Item.
*   Rough Draft Work Items are NOT listed in the CCGs official roadmap.
*   Contributions to the Rough Draft by CCG members are moderated in a manner suitable to the medium, under the guidance of the Work Item editors.
*   Work Item editors must ensure that all substantial commitments to the Rough Draft are made by members that have signed the CCGs Contributors Agreement.
*   Editors may iterate these Rough Draft Work Items at their initial location until they are ready, but the goal should be to transition them after approval as a Work Item to become ReSpec documents in a CCG repo as soon as reasonably possible.


#### Unreleased Draft

**Unreleased Draft** — A version of a COMMUNITY REPORT Work Item that exists as a repo in the official CCG GitHub Community, for iteration by CCG members through discussion, issues, and pull requests.



*   When the editors of a Rough Draft Work Item agree that a version of a Rough Draft Work Item is ready for Github, and it has been formatted in ReSpec format (or appropriate format for destination such as IETF draft format), they may ask the CCG chairs to create a repo for the Work Item in the CCG Github Community, [as described here](https://w3c-ccg.github.io/create_repo.html). 
*   Unreleased Draft Work Items ARE listed in the CCGs official roadmap, and the repo description begins with “UNRELEASED DRAFT:”
*   Issues & pull requests to the Unreleased Draft are moderated by the Work Item editors, as per W3C github cultural practices, including transparency and public documentation of work item meetings. (details TBW).


#### Released Draft

**Released Draft **— A commit of the Work Item is tagged with a Git release number. This is a frozen moment in time during the collaboration.



*   When the editors of a Work item believe that the collaboration has reached some milestone (say for broader commentary by other CCG members or to the broader community), at their discretion they may mark a particular version of the repo with a release tag. If the Work Item itself contains a version number (e.g. in its specification text), then that version must be increased with the commit following the release tag; work then continues on that next version. The repo description should be changed to begin with “RELEASED DRAFT:” to show evidence of the evolution of this Work Item.
*   Release numbering must follow SemVer [https://semver.org](https://semver.org). Work items that are WG Specifications or WG Notes track (for future transitions to the  standards-track W3C Working Group Process) must be numbered below 1.0.0. Alternatively, drafts destined for non-W3C standards track may use the appropriate numbering system for the  intended standards organization.
*   Editors should submit PR to [https://github.com/w3c-ccg/community/blob/master/work_items.md](https://github.com/w3c-ccg/community/blob/master/work_items.md) to update the work item stage and version number.
*   The editors may continue to update with new releases numbers as needed.


#### Published Draft

**Published Draft **— A RELEASED DRAFT of a community report Work Item that is formally listed and published through the W3C publication process on the [W3C Credentials Community Page](https://www.w3.org/community/credentials/) and is shared on various W3C mailing lists and reports



*   Prior to publishing, the Editors must verify that all substantive contributors to the RELEASED DRAFT have signed the CCGs Contributors Agreement, and request that the chairs publish the draft to the W3C.
*   The chairs determine when a released draft is ready to listed as Published Draft and add the [W3C Credentials Community Page](https://www.w3.org/community/credentials/).
*   Once published the repo description should begin with “PUBLISHED DRAFT:”


#### Final Report

**Final Report** — A PUBLISHED DRAFT that has been vetted by the chairs, and then also approved as a FINAL REPORT by the broader community group and the W3C staff. Upon acceptance, this Work Item is complete. 



*   When a COMMUNITY REPORT is final, and work on that version is complete or a hand-off to a WG is imminent, the Work Item editors finalize any IPR commitments.
*   The chairs review the PUBLISHED DRAFT for consideration as a FINAL REPORT and post the proposal to become a FINAL REPORT an email to the CCG discussion list for approval.
*   Once proposed, the community group will discuss it for a period of at least one week. This discussion may take place on the mailing list as well as on the regular conference call at the Chairs discretion.
*   If there is sufficient community support for the PUBLISHED DRAFT and there are no principled objections, the chairs at their discretion will submit the PUBLISHED DRAFT to the W3C staff as a FINAL REPORT.
*   W3C Staff have final approval for all FINAL REPORTS listed in the [W3C Credentials Community Page](https://www.w3.org/community/credentials/). 
*   If accepted by the W3C staff, the repo description will be changed to “FINAL REPORT:” and the work item is now closed.


### Ongoing Community Draft Stages


#### Create an Ongoing Community Draft

Propose a CG Work Item with the intent to make it an Ongoing Community Draft (such as a CG Registry). The proposal would pass per the CG's documented consensus process.

W3C leadership may propose a process for ongoing community drafts, which would apply to Ongoing Community Drafts in this CG.

Any normative registry work items should be chartered by a W3C working group and shall be run according to that charter. Charter should include plans for releasing snapshots of the work item.


